li.p:
 The volume of the pan from part (a) is

V(p)=\left(\sqrt{\dfrac{A}{3p}}\right)\left(p\sqrt{\dfrac{A}{3p}}\right)
\dfrac{\sqrt{Ap}}{\sqrt{3}(1+p)}
=\left(\dfrac{A}{3}\right)^{3/2}\dfrac{\sqrt{p}}{1+p}

Since

\diff{}{p}\left\{\dfrac{\sqrt{p}}{1+p}\right\}=\dfrac{\half (1+p)/\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{p}}{(1+p)^2}
=\dfrac{\sqrt{p}\left(\dfrac{1}{p}-1\right)}{2(1+p)^2}

the volume is increasing with p for p \lt 1 and decreasing with p for
p \gt 1. So the maximum volume is achieved for p=1 (a square base).

solution.p:
The area enclosed by the shapes, when the square is made from a length of size \ell, is


A(\ell)&=\dfrac{\ell^2}{16}+\dfrac{(L-\ell)^2}{4\pi}

We want to find the global max and min for this function, given the constraint 0 \leq \ell \leq L, so we find its derivative:
A'(\ell)&=\dfrac{\ell}{8} -\dfrac{L-\ell}{2\pi}
         =\dfrac{\pi+4}{8\pi}\ell-\dfrac{L}{2\pi}

Now, we find the critical point.
A'(\ell)&=0

\frac{\pi+4}{8\pi}\ell&=\frac{L}{2\pi}

\ell&=\frac{4L}{\pi+4}

When \ell \lt \frac{4L}{\pi+4}, A'(\ell) \lt 0, and when
\ell \gt \frac{4L}{\pi+4}, A'(\ell) \gt 0. So, A(\ell) is decreasing until \ell=\frac{4L}{\pi+4}, then increasing. That means our critical point \ell=\frac{4L}{\pi+4}
is a local minimum.
